ce:section.ce:para:
To appraise the stability and consistency of the method, the intra-day and inter-day experiments were investigated. As indicated in Table S3, the relative standard deviation (RSD) values of the intra-day and inter-day for Ag+ were less than 2.75 and 4.04 %, indicating that the method (the N-CDs) for the Ag+ assay had a certain degree of reality and stability. In addition, corresponding RSD values for the GSH determination did not exceed 3.65 or 4.95 % (Table S4), which elaborated the repeatability and feasibility of the N-CDs@Ag+ for the determination of GSH. Moreover, to further verify the reliability and practicality of the N-CDs or N-CDs@Ag+ probe responding to Ag+ or GSH in real samples, water samples (drinking water, tap water and lake water for Ag+) and fruit samples (tomatoes, red grapes and oranges for GSH) were used. The recovery and RSD values of Ag+ assay by the N-CDs were changed in the ranges of 94.6 %–107.9 % and 0.60 %–3.90 % (Table 1
                        ), hinting that the N-CDs exhibited a potential capability to monitor Ag+ in water samples. Likewise, the N-CDs@Ag+ probe had also high accuracy for the GSH sensing in fruit samples due to good recoveries (from 91.3 % to 108.7 %) and low RSD (less than 3.99 %) (Table 2
                        ). Moreover, the results of Ag+ and GSH detections by the N-CDs and N-CDs@Ag+ probes were consistent with those by the standard colorimetry and HPLC methods in three actual samples (Tables S5 and S6). Meanwhile, t-test results represented that two methods didn't exist significance difference for the Ag+ and GSH assays, because the values of t (2.89 for lake water; 1.70, 1.97 and 2.21 for orange, red grape and tomato) were less than that of t
                        0.05, 2 (4.30). Above results suggested that the N-CDs and N-CDs@Ag+ probes had great reliability for the Ag+ and GSH assays in real samples.
